
What is Simple Factory Pattern?

The Simple Factory Pattern is a design pattern that provides a static method to create objects without exposing the instantiation logic to the client. 
It is a simplified version of the Factory Pattern, where a single factory class is responsible for creating objects based on some input parameters.

In the Simple Factory Pattern, we have a Factory class that contains a static method that takes some input parameters and returns an instance of a specific type of object based on those parameters.

The Simple Factory Pattern is useful when we want to create objects without exposing the creation logic to the client, and when we have a limited number of object types that can be created.

In summary, the Simple Factory Pattern is a design pattern that provides a static method to create objects without exposing the instantiation logic to the client. 
It is a simplified version of the Factory Pattern, where a single factory class is responsible for creating objects based on some input parameters.

Simple Factory Idea

One class → decides which object to create using if/else, switch, or any other logic.

When to Use Simple Factory?
Use Simple Factory when:
Need to create objects without exposing creation logic
Have a limited number of object types that can be created


Simple Factory

👉 One kitchen decides:

“Burger or Pizza?”

WHY Simple Factory :
✔ Decoupled : 
The client code is decoupled from the specific classes that are being instantiated. 
The client code only interacts with the factory class, which is responsible for creating the objects. 
This allows us to change the implementation of the factory class without affecting the client code.

without simple factory, the client code would be directly dependent on the concrete classes (e.g., BurgerOrder, PizzaOrder).
example client code without simple factory:
var burgerOrder = new BurgerOrder("Santhosh", "Cheese", "Medium");

full client code without simple factory:

✔ Flexible : With the Simple Factory Pattern, we can easily add new types of objects without modifying the client code.

example client code with simple factory:

var orderFactory = new OrderFactory();
var burgerOrder = orderFactory.Create("Burger", "Santhosh", "Cheese", "Medium");

full client code with simple factory:
var orderFactory = new OrderFactory();
var burgerOrder = orderFactory.Create("Burger", "Santhosh", "Cheese", "Medium");
var pizzaOrder = orderFactory.Create("Pizza", "Santhosh", "Pepperoni", "Large");
When we want to add a new type of order (e.g., SaladOrder), we can simply add a new case to the factory method without modifying the client code.


EXAMPLE:
// Factory Interface
public interface IOrderFactory
{
	IOrder Create(string orderType, string customerName, string item, string size);
}

// Concrete Factory

public class OrderFactory : IOrderFactory
{
	public IOrder Create(string orderType, string customerName, string item, string size)
	{
		switch (orderType)
		{
			case "Burger":
				return new BurgerOrder(customerName, item, size);
			case "Pizza":
				return new PizzaOrder(customerName, item, size);
			default:
				throw new ArgumentException("Invalid order type");
		}
	}
}


